06966nam a22009255i 9783110725339DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107253397 a10.1515/97831107253392doi  a(DE-B1597)571511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a808.02090200aIn Search of the Culprit :bAspects of Medieval Authorship /ced. by Stefanie Gropper, Lukas Rösli. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (298 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAndere Ästhetik - Studien ,x2749-652X ;v100tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Contents -- tIn Search of the Culprit. Aspects of Medieval Authorship -- t"... who is the author of this book?" -- tThe Primal Scribe -- tThe 'Heteronomous Authorship' of Icelandic Saga Literature -- tStylometry and the Faded Fingerprints of Saga Authors -- tAnonymity and the Textual Construction of Authority in Prosimetrum -- tThe Persistence of the Humanistic Legacy -- tSpectres of Agency -- tA Theory of Early Modern Authorship -- tShakespeare's Medieval Co-Authors -- tConceptions of Authorship -- tThe Best-Written Saga and the Absence of its Author -- tFigures and Charts -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Works -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tIndex of Matters0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aDespite various poststructuralist rejections of the idea of a singular author-genius, the question of a textual archetype that can be assigned to a named author is still a common scholarly phantasm. The Romantic idea that an author created a text or even a work autonomously is transferred even to pre-modern literature today. This ignores the fact that the transmission of medieval and early modern literature creates variances that could not be justified by means of singular authorships. The present volume offers new theoretical approaches from English, German, and Scandinavian studies to provide a historically more adequate approach to the question of authorship in premodern literary cultures. Authorship is no longer equated with an extra-textual entity, but is instead considered a narratological, inner- and intertextual function that can be recognized in the retrospectively established beginnings of literature as well as in the medial transformation of texts during the early days of printing. The volume is aimed at interested scholars of all philologies, especially those dealing with the Middle Ages or Early Modern Period.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Sonderforschungsbereich 1391 Andere Ästhetik  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aAutorschaft als theoretisches Konzept. 4aVormoderne Autorschaft. 4aVormoderne Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAuthorship as a Theoretical Concept.  aPremodern Authorship.  aPremodern Literature.1 aBamberger, Gudrun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Matthias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBjörnsson, Sigurður Ingibergur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEggertsdóttir, Margrét, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlauser, Jürg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGropper, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGropper, Stefanie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelgason, Jón Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r